On Monday 05 April 2004 17:55, Jason Rogers wrote:
&gt; While that is true, it is irrelevant to his example test (unless I
&gt; missed something about my &quot;simple&quot; explanation and your correction)
&gt; because he wasn&#39;t reassigning the original variable.  But alas, I
&gt; believe we are off-topic now.  You are correct in the sense that it
&gt; reduces memory usage, but as a habit (personally) I feel it should be
&gt; avoided.  If I must optimize, this is surely a good optimization place.
&gt; For example:
&gt;
&gt;   BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
&gt;   String line = null;
&gt;   while ( (line = reader.readLine()) != null ) {
&gt;     doSomethingWith(line);
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt; is _MUCH_ cheaper (in terms of allocation) than:
&gt;
&gt;   BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
&gt;   while ( reader.ready() ) {
&gt;     String line = reader.readLine();
&gt;     doSomethingWith(line);
&gt;   }

I don&#39;t see why you think this: in both cases all the interesting allocation
happens inside readLine. Where the local variable is declared is going
to make essentially no difference. [Internally, &quot;line&quot; is a reference value
of fixed size, allocated in the method&#39;s stack-frame; it&#39;s not an object
allocated in the heap [1], so going round the loop redeclaring it doesn&#39;t
burn store. It would be different if we were in a language with full lexical
scoping like Scheme or Pop11, and the variable was captured by a closure,
but we aren&#39;t and we cant.]

[1] I can imagine an implementation that allocated stack-frames on the
heap, as NJSML does, but even that doesn&#39;t allocate individual variables
on the heap in cases like this.

